"# Book of Sick Composition

A ramp from easy to pro. Every chapter takes one Motoi lib, opens with what the lib does and why it exists, and then walks a stack of problems: nothing to something, something to more, more to a whole thing.

This is a small book. Eight chapters — one per lib — instead of the usual sixteen. The trade Alfred wanted: fewer chapters, each complete, each with real code that runs against the real runtime. No stubs. No pseudo-code. Every verb is a verb the reference documents. Every code sample was designed to run against `bin/motoi eval`.

## What each chapter looks like

Every chapter has the same shape:

- **Why this lib exists.** Two or three paragraphs. What the lib does, what pain it solves, what mental model to bring to it.
- **Problem 1.** Easy. Three to five lines. Nothing to something.
- **Problem 2.** Slightly harder. Eight to fifteen lines. Something to more.
- **Problem 3.** Composition. Twenty to thirty lines. Real feature, real thinking.
- **Problem 4 (pro).** A small complete thing. Sixty lines at the outside. If you understand problem 4 you know the lib.
- **Capstone.** One more, showing the lib in idiomatic use — how a working programmer reaches for it.
- **What's next.** A short bridge to the next chapter.

## The 8 chapters

1. **The Base** — car, cdr, cons, define, lambda, if. The seven-verb kit.
2. **Lists You Move Around** — map, filter, reduce. The pipeline shape.
3. **Higher-Order** — functions that take functions and return functions.
4. **Recursion Without Fear** — the pattern that stops needing loops.
5. **The Frame** — fb, text, and drawing your first picture.
6. **The World Loop** — big-bang, on-tick, to-draw, on-key.
7. **Entities on the Field** — world/spawn, entity/*, physics you get free.
8. **Sound and Music** — note/strike, synth/chord, and a song from scratch.

## The Speak & Spell measure

Alfred once said Motoi should feel like the most advanced Speak & Spell — deterministic, warm, tangible, rewarding, not trying to be more than it is. A kid should feel like they made something out of nothing, and they should be able to see how.

Every problem in this book was designed against that measure. Read one, type it in, run it, watch the small thing happen. Change one number, run it again, watch the small thing change. That is the shape. That is why this book exists.

## What this book is not

- It is not a reference. The reference is `scheme/MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat`; look there for signatures.
- It is not a philosophy. Motoi's philosophy lives in Book of Self and Book of Introspection.
- It is not exhaustive. There are entire libs (AI steering, topology, calculus) that are not covered here. This is the on-ramp.
- It is not a game engine tutorial. It is a language tutorial that uses game verbs because game verbs are fun.

## Provenance

Every code sample cites a verb in the reference. No LLM invented a signature. Every problem was authored under intent — no scraping, no external corpora, no pattern-copying from other tutorials. The book is a self-contained artifact that Motoi can read, that a kid can read, that a working programmer can read.
")
